Munkres Topology section 21 example 1 shows that $\Bbb R^{\omega}$ in the box topology is not metrizable. (The hidden problems have been solved, but I have another new problem. Please see below.) I don't understand this sentence "the point $a_n$ cannot belong to $B'$ because its $n$th coordinate $x_{nn}$ does not belong to the interval $(-x_{nn},x_{nn})$."//We have an exercise in section 20 which gives a sequence of points in $\Bbb R^{\omega}$ converging to $0$. $z_1 = (1,1,0,0...), z_2 = (1/2,1/2,0,0...), z_3= (1/3,1/3,0,0...),...$. Could anyone explain it?//Let $a_n = (1/n, 1/n, ...)$ and $(a_n)$ be a sequence of points in $\Bbb R^{\omega}$. Does $(a_n)$ converge to $0$ in the box topology of $\Bbb R^{\omega}$? To show the sequence lemma does not hold for $\Bbb R^{\omega}$, we need to show that there exists(?) $x \in  ar{A}$ s.t. for any sequence $(x_n)$ in $A$, $x_n 
ot 	o x$. (I'm not sure if we only need to prove there exists such $x \in  ar{A}$ or we actually need to prove for all $x\in  ar{A}$?) Pick $0\in  ar{A}$ and $a_n$ is arbitrary. $$a_1 = (x_{11}, x_{21}, x_{31}, \cdots, x_{i1}, \cdots),\ a_2 = (x_{12}, x_{22}, x_{32}, \cdots, x_{i2}, \cdots),\ a_3 = (x_{13}, x_{23}, x_{33}, \cdots, x_{i3}, \cdots),\\cdots\ a_n = (x_{1n}, x_{2n}, x_{3n}, \cdots, x_{in}, \cdots)\ \cdots$$ $B' = (-x_{11},x_{11})	imes (-x_{21}, x_{21})	imes (-x_{31},x_{31})	imes \cdots 	imes(-x_{i1},x_{i1}) 	imes \cdots$ . $a_1 
ot \in B'$ because $x_{11}
ot \in (-x_{11},x_{11})$. Similarly, $x_n 
ot \in B'$ because $x_{nn}
ot \in (-x_{nn},x_{nn})$ for any $n$.

